Paul,<br><br>
I feel that participation or non-participation it is a matter of personal choice guided/influenced by conscience, fear, obligation, religous conviction, wellspring, and all the rest of those things that directly and indirectly guide our decisions.<br><br>
My choice to enlist in the Army, knowing full well that I could be sent to 'Nam, was guided by patriotic obligation, a &quot;military&quot; background, curiosity to see what war was all about, a desire to experience that which my father and grandfather did, and maybe looking for a high.<br><br>
What I know of the choices others made is scanty. In the Forum section of this dialog, I began to understand what guided a Mennonite CO in his choice, an unshakable and sincere religous conviction for which I had the deepest respect. Curiously, he understood my choices as well, and respected and honored them. I continue to hold the man in the highest regard. <br><br>
If you note carefully, the relationship I enjoyed with my Mennonite friend was one of mutual respect from which understanding could be drawn. We could debate with honor. Those who made choices other than the one I made and who do not have mutual respect are not worthy of the time of day. I often wonder if they have the capacity to even repect themselves.<br><br>
So, Paul, that is my view. It is a matter of choice. If opposing choices strive for understanding, it can only be accomplished through mutual respect. <br><br>
